Dr. Wei.
Nice meeting you today and thank you for sharing that information with me.
I have a page in which RUV is described in the context of normalization=E2=
=80=94see
Section 2 here: Statistical Analysis of Genomic Data for Biotech
Applications <https://reanalysis.netlify.app/>

The RUV paper I was referring to is

   - Molania R, Foroutan M, Gagnon-Bartsch JA, Gandolfo LC, Jain A, Sinha
   A, Olshansky G, Dobrovic A, Papenfuss AT, Speed TP (2023). =E2=80=9CRemo=
ving
   unwanted variation from large-scale RNA sequencing data with PRPS.=E2=80=
=9D *Nature
   Biotechnology*, *41*(1), 82-95. doi:10.1038/s41587-022-01440-w
   https://doi.org/10.1038/s41587-022-01440-w,
   https://doi.org/10.1038/s41587-022-01440-w.

In section 2.2 of the page, there is a link to a Claude AI summary for
the Molania
paper.  Examining the figures of Section 2, Detailed Results by Dataset, is
sufficient to get the gist of the issues around unwanted variability.

Determining the number of external locations we need to examine to make a
statement about generalizability requires careful thought.  For classical
statistics methodologies to apply we need the site or location effects to
reduce to a metric, and we require data collected from a random subset of
sites.  That would be difficult, if not impossible.  I think we should
establish a way to adjust the data to detect and remove location effects.

Thanks again for sharing your work with me.  I look forward to learning
more.


All the best,

Francois




